Cases in various countries:
Asia
---
Sri Lanka. 2 Apr 2014. Dengue as of 1 Apr 2014, 6627 cases; Deaths 10. An island-wide campaign for public education and to eliminate vector mosquito breeding sites is being carried out from 2-8 Apr 2014.
http://www.sundaytimes.lk/news/latest-news/48131.html

[Maps of Sri Lanka can be seen at http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/srilanka.pdf and
http://healthmap.org/r/1A-B. - Mod.TY]

Indian Ocean
---
Mayotte. 4 Apr 2014. Dengue 28 cases in Mayotte, 23 others imported from Comoros, 3 other cases origin undetermined.
http://www.linfo.re/049-Ocean-Indien/402-Societe/634925-Dengue-a-Mayotte-9-nouveaux-cas-en-une-semaine [in French]

[A map showing the location of Mayotte in the Indian Ocean can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2390179,16272. - Mod.TY]

Africa
---
Ethiopia (Gode zone, Somalia region). 31 Mar 2014. Dengue 126 cases since mid-January 2014.
http://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/Humanitarian%20Bulletin_31%20March%202014.pdf

[A map of Ethiopia showing the Somalia region can be accessed at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Somali_Region. - Mod.TY]

Nigeria (Edo state). 2 Apr 2014. Dengue. A 15 year old girl thought to have been infected with Ebola virus actually died of DHF.
http://allafrica.com/stories/201404021178.html

[Normally, ProMED-mail does not report single cases of DHF, but this unique case was initially thought to be due to an Ebola virus infection. Reports of dengue cases in Africa generally, and Nigeria specifically, are relatively rare.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Nigeria can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2390179,38426. - Mod.TY]

